quote: "Happy Birthday, Dear Julian... "
"Happy Birthday to you."
"And many more." Doctor, I really must congratulate you. You have a fascinating mind.
Look, I'm sorry, but I don't have time for this.
But it's a party. And it's all for you.
You should try to enjoy yourself. It's your birthday.
Garak, get me over to the engineering station. Now.
Sorry, my dear.
There has to be a way to reactivate the station's central computer network.
Any ideas on how to go about doing that?

My Engineering extension classes at Starfleet Medical focused mainly on starship operations, but I think if I can re-route the primary command processor to bypass the disabled systems, I should be able to get it operational.
So which panel accesses the computer?
If you were really Garak, you could tell me. In fact, you could probably fix this computer without my help.
But I'm not really Garak, am I? I'm just another part of you.
Help me get this panel off.
Tennis balls?
This station is in worse shape then we thought.
Garak... (holds out his hand for help) One of these panels has to have the computer controls behind it. I just have to find the right one.
(doesn't move to help him) Face it, Doctor, there's no way to repair the damage. It's too extensive.
If you won't help me, I'll do it myself.
I'd be more than willing to help, if I thought it would accomplish anything, but you're only delaying the inevitable.
That doesn't sound like the Garak I know.
Doctor, we've been through this. I'm not Garak. I'm you.
It doesn't sound like me either.

I've been thinking... Why has the Lethean let you live? He killed everyone else who could've helped me. And exactly what part of me are you supposed to represent? My conscience, my curiosity, my sense of humor?
You tell me.
I don't think you're any part of me. In fact, I don't think you belong here at all.
So that leaves me with one question. Who are you?
You've put up an entertaining struggle, Doctor.
I'm glad you're enjoying yourself.
But now it's time for you to make things easy on yourself.
You mean just give up? I don't think so.
Why not? Isn't that what you've always done? Remember, Doctor, I'm inside your head. I know all about you.
When you were younger, you wanted to be a tennis player, didn't you?
I wasn't good enough to play professionally.
You can't lie to me. Not in here. You were good enough. But you knew your parents wouldn't approve. So you gave up. And became a doctor instead.
I love medicine.
But you loved tennis more. And what about medical school? You should've been first in your class, what went wrong?
I made a mistake on the final exam.
You mistook a pre-ganglionic fiber for a post-ganglionic nerve.
That's right.
But pre-ganglionic fibers and post- ganglionic nerves aren't anything alike. Any first year medical student can tell them apart. You purposely gave the wrong answer.
That's ridiculous.
You didn't want to be number one in your class. You couldn't take the pressure.
That's not true.
Isn't it? Then let's talk about Lieutenant Dax. You like her, don't you?
Dax is my friend.
She could've been more if you'd tried a little harder. But you'd rather give up than fight, wouldn't you?
We'll see about that.
Wait. Where are you going?
What do you think you're doing?
The mistake I made was trying to repair the station from Ops. That may be the nerve center of the real station, but this... (indicates the Infirmary) Is the center of my world.
Get away from that panel.
(begins working on the cables) Or what? You'll kill me. Go ahead. What's stopping you? You've had plenty of chances. It must not be as easy for you as you make it sound.
That's better. You know, you don't look half as threatening in normal light.
Take a close look, Doctor. You're dying. Why can't you just accept it?

Because that's what you want me to do. You may be inside my head, but you don't understand me nearly as well as you think you do. Take Dax... I do have feelings for her, but the important thing is... she's my friend. And I wouldn't trade that friendship for anything. And as far as my career is concerned... I may have been a good tennis player, but I'm a great doctor. Maybe I could've been first in my class, but it wouldn't have made any difference in my life. I still would've chosen this assignment. This is where I belong. Computer activate quarantine field three-Jay.
You can't do this.
I can do anything I want. It's my mind. Begin sterilization.
Noooooooo.
Julian... He's awake.
Vital signs have stabilized. His brain wave activity's normal.
Welcome back, Doctor.
You'll never believe where I've been.
As for the real Altovar, he triggered a security alert when he broke into the Infirmary. He barely got two meters before Odo arrested him.
It sounds like he was a lot more dangerous in your mind than he was in the real world.
Actually, I did some checking on Letheans. Their telepathic attacks are almost always fatal. I guess I was lucky.
Cardassians don't believe in luck, Doctor. You survived because you were strong.
I didn't feel strong. One thing's for sure, after experiencing life at the age of a hundred plus, turning thirty doesn't seem so bad anymore.

In that case, Happy Birthday. You know, Doctor, the thing I find most fascinating about this entire incident is how your unconscious mind chose people you know to represent the various parts of your personality.
It did make things interesting.
What I find interesting is how your mind ended up casting me in the role of the villain.
I wouldn't read too much into that, Garak.
How can I not? To think, after all this time, all our lunches together... you still don't trust me.
There's hope for you yet, Doctor.
Hey, what are you looking at?

quote: National Guard units are mobilizing now and should reach Sanctuary District "A" within the hour. Governor Chen has issued a statement saying the uprising will be quelled and the Sanctuary District secured. It's still not clear how this riot began, though rumors of mounting tensions have been filtering out of the district for weeks.
This is great. We're on every channel. I bet they're even watching this in China. (reacting to the reports) What do they sound so surprised for? You treat people like animals, you get bit.
Let me through.
Hey, who said you could come in here?
It's okay. Let him in.
You know this gimmie?
He's a friend.
You... join your friends.
I'm glad to see you're all right...
So much for our peaceful demonstration...
I know this isn't what we talked about... but it's what happened -- and now we have to deal with it.
How? It's a madhouse out there... and this building is crawling with ghosts.
I know. That's the first thing we have to fix. I want you to go out and find some gimmies, people you know, people who can be trusted to help guard the hostages.
If we leave it to the ghosts, there's no telling what could happen.
I think I know just the people you're looking for.
Good. We're going to need them.
Hey, Bell. You're really missing something here.

... Sanctuary Residents have looted the district's food distribution centers, and there are reports of at least a dozen fires. Many of the district employees fleeing the riot have been reported injured and several have yet to be accounted for. There's been no official count of injuries among Sanctuary residents, however satellite pictures show a number of possible casualties.
This is terrible.
I've got to get down there.
What are you talking about?
My friends are in there.
I know. But there's nothing you can do for them.
I have to try.
It's too dangerous, Jadzia. You could get hurt.
Maybe. But at least I'll have done something. I just can't sit here, watching that place burn, knowing my friends are inside.
Listen... I have some friends in the police department. When things settle down a little bit, I'll talk to them about--
I can't wait that long. By the time things settle down, my friends could be hurt... or even killed. They don't belong in there. None of those people do.
Jadzia, wait.
I'll come with you. (turns off the Interface) I guess I'm getting tired of just watching, too.

First Officer's Log, supplemental. Somehow Sisko, Dax, and Bashir have altered Earth's history. We have no choice but to send an away team into the past, to try to find them, and to correct the changes to the timeline. The only problem is, we're not exactly sure where to look... or when.

According to our computer simulations, the degree of temporal displacement is directly proportional to the number of chroniton particles interacting with the transporter beam. Unfortunately, there's no way to know the exact concentration of particles at the time of the accident, but I've narrowed it down to ten possibilities, each one corresponding to a different time frame. One of them has to be right. We'll just have to hope we find the right one before we run out of chroniton particles.
I feel ridiculous.
Well, it does effectively disguise your Bajoran heritage.
If anyone asks, just say you broke your nose.
Better yet, don't say anything. Let me do the talking.
That's fine with me.
Good luck.
Energize...
as Kira and O'Brien MATERIALIZE just inside an alley. It's late, and no one's around... O'Brien immediately takes out his TRICORDER and starts scanning.

quote: I asked them to help.
And who invited you?
I did.
We needed people we could trust in here.
What's that supposed to mean?
How many Ghosts do you know who you can really trust?
(thinks it over for a beat) One. Me. And that's enough.
No, it isn't. Not here. Not now.
Someone's got to guard the building, watch the exits. Keep an eye on the hostages when we need to sleep.
Okay, okay. You made your point. Just keep them out of my hair.
The important thing is to decide what we're going to do with those hostages.
You don't have to worry about that. I've got it all figured out.
I bet you do.
And just to prove I'm not a bad guy, I'm going to let you two in on it. It's simple.
We trade the hostages for our freedom. We get amnesty, a handful of credit chips, and a flight to... anywhere we want. Personally, I'm thinking Tasmania.
Tasmania.
Errol Flynn was born there. You go where you want; I'll go where I want.
Yeah, and as soon as we step off the plane, they lock us up.
Besides, we can't just think about ourselves. There're ten thousand people living in here.
Yeah, well they can find their own hostages.
No, Gabe is right. This is an opportunity. To make ourselves heard. To let people on the outside know what's going on in here.
You want to make demands, I'll give you some demands. We tell them if they want the hostages back, they've got to close down the Sanctuaries.
That's right. And reinstate the Federal Employment Act.

Sounds good to me. Why don't you have them throw in some silk shirts and a penthouse in Singapore while you're at it? Jobs. You guys want jobs? When are you going to figure it out? There are no jobs. Not for us, anyway.
They'll find us jobs. They'll have to. After tonight, they won't be able to ignore us anymore.
All right, we'll do it your way; see what happens. I'll log onto the Interface. I'll tell them we want the District closed. See what happens.
Not you. Him.
Funny, I would've nominated you.
What? Is something wrong with me? I can be as eloquent as the next guy.
I'm sure you can. But they won't be able to dismiss Webb as easily as they would you or me. He's got the face. He's got the family. He's the guy next door. And that's what they need to see.

Here we go. My name is Michael Webb. I used to be a Plant Manager at ChemTech Industries. I'm speaking for the residents of Sanctuary District "A." We're holding six hostages... we don't want to hurt them... all we want is --
What happened?
Someone's cut off our access to the Interface...
I knew it! I knew this was a waste of time. They don't care. No one cares about us.
Why should they? You're all a bunch of losers.
What did you say?
He didn't say anything.
You heard me. I called you a loser. Because that's what you are. And this time, you're going to lose big.
Okay, that's enough.
Check your E-mail, buddy. You're a loser, too.
If you want to get out of here, you'd better hope you're wrong.
Quiet down, Vin. You're only making things worse.

I just want these guys to know what they're in for. I bet the National Guard's already got this place surrounded. And sooner or later, they're going to roll right in here, and you people won't even slow them down.
(perfectly rational, re: Vin) I really think we should kill this guy.
Maybe you'd better talk to the police first.
Mister Webb, I'm Detective Preston of the S.F.P.D...
Did you shut off our access to the Interface?
I'm afraid that's department policy in these types of situations. But it does give us a chance to talk one- on-one...
All right, let's talk.
First, I want to see the hostages.
What for?
I need to make sure they're okay. You said you weren't going to hurt them... I need to know I can count on that.
They want to see a hostage, let's show them a hostage.
Take a good look, lady. We've got five more just like her. And if we don't get what we want, they're going to get hurt.
Everyone stands motionless, unsure what to do. Sisko moves toward the counter, behind which B.C. is holding Lee. Sisko is carrying a shotgun, but doesn't aim it at B.C...
I think you've made your point.
Have I, Detective?
I'd say so...
Good...
Now if you don't mind, I'd like to speak to Mister Webb again...
Why would I mind... ?
All right, Detective, I'm here.
Your friend has quite a temper...
That's because he's angry... we all are.
B.C., let me ask you something...
Go ahead.
Why do I get the feeling you're not going to be happy until you've hurt one of those hostages?
I've got to admit, the thought is tempting... it might alleviate some of the stress I'm feeling...
I think you'd better find another way to deal with your stress... it's sure to be a lot healthier for you in the long run...
No kidding... Let me ask you something... You think it looks better like this... -- or like this?
It's your head... and your decision...
Hey, Gabe... Detective Preston wants to meet with me...
When?
Now... by the main gate.
Mind if I join you?
I was hoping you'd say that.
Keep an eye on the hostages...
Got it. Good luck.
... it's been a long night. You two must be exhausted.
We're okay. We could use some breakfast come morning.
Breakfast for ten thousand? That's a lot of take-out... but in the interest of friendship, I'll do what I can.
No hostage, no food -- is that what you're saying?
Not at all. You'll get the food either way. But giving up one of the hostages would show good faith... besides, you'd still have five left.
Those hostages aren't going anywhere until we get what we want.
Which is what?
We want the Sanctuaries closed down... and the Federal Employment Act reinstated.
That's asking a lot...
I don't think so. All we want is to get out from behind these walls... to stop having to depend on handouts...
That's right. All we're asking for is a chance to get back on our feet again. We don't deserve to be locked up in here.
Obviously I can't promise anything, but I'll see to it that the Governor hears your demands.
You do that.
Put me through to the Governor...

Bell? Yes, we came in together.

When I first started working here, I processed a woman who had a warrant out on her for abandoning her kid. She couldn't take care of him, so she left him with a family she worked for over in the Marina. I felt so sorry for her I didn't log her in... I just let her disappear into the Sanctuary.
That was very kind of you...
Almost got fired when my supervisor found out.
What happened to the woman?
I don't know... but I think about her all the time. Ever since then I've just... done my job, you know? And tried not to let it get to me.
It's not your fault things are the way they are.
Everybody tells themselves that... and nothing ever changes...
Hold it!

Thank you...
Uh-oh...
Wow...
Danny...
He was outside looking for you.
Your mother and Jeannie... are they okay?
They're fine; they're with the Petersons.
So what are you doing here?
I wanted to be with you.
All right, you can stay for a while... but when I tell you to go, I don't want any arguments.
I found this glucajen in what was left of the clinic. You should be feeling better soon.
Thank you...
Is that your family?
Yeah...
Let him see.
Nice looking bunch, huh?
Absolutely.
Right now those two kids are sitting home wondering if they'll ever see their dad again.
I realize this won't make what you're going through any easier... but something good will come from all this.
You think they're just going to close down the Sanctuary and let you walk out of here?
No... but I know that someday there won't be any need for places like this.
I hope you're right. Even though it'll mean I'll be out of a job.
I just want to get home, you know?
I know... so do I.
The Governor has assured me that if you let the hostages go, the charges against you will be reduced to incitement to riot.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: That's it? What about closing the Sanctuary, what about jobs?
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: The Governor intends to form a committee to look into the problems facing District residents.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: So what you're telling us is that nothing is going to change.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: I wouldn't say that. But change takes time.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: You've run out of time.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: Gentlemen, if I were you I would seriously consider taking this offer.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: Or else what?
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: The Governor is not going to let this situation continue forever.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: Tell him that if he wants to see those hostages again, he's going to have to do better...
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: Tough talk...
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: I was bluffing...
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: I couldn't tell.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: I hope she couldn't either.
scene: 26   EXT. NEAR THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: Try opening that menu.
It just brings me back to the same screen. There doesn't seem to be any way to get past the lockout and log onto the Net.
There has to be.
How can you be certain?
Because according to history, the residents were able to get onto the Net and tell their side of the story. Millions of people watched.
No one here's been able to get past the lockout.
Maybe it was Bell... and if he did it, we have to also.
Listen up, everybody. A couple of dims just brought us a little present.
I don't know about you fellas... but I'm in love.
Jadzia...
Julian...
You know her?
Story of my life... all the good ones are taken...
You remember my friend Gabe... ?
Gabe Bell... it's good to see you again.
It's good to see you...
Allow me to introduce myself...
Biddle Coleridge...
Biddle?
Hey.
I didn't say a word.
I've been looking all over for you.
You obviously don't live here... so how did you get inside?
I managed to recode my I.D. card so I could get past the Sanitation Department checkpoint.
You crawled in through the sewers? She must really like these guys.
She must really like these guys.
You should sit down. You look exhausted.
Too bad... (off Webb's questioning look) I really think me and her could've had something special...
-- so what you're saying is that even if I could get you out of the Sanctuary, you wouldn't leave.
Those hostages have to be protected, whatever the cost.
You said that one of the men who brought you here took your combadge...
That's right. And it's set to emit a subspace distress signal.
Julian, I want you to help Dax find the men who took her combadge... and then I want you both to get away from this place.
But if the Defiant locks on to my distress signal... and we're not together...
As soon as the hostages are in police custody, I'll try to get back to the beam-in site.
If for some reason I can't make it, you'll have to leave without me.

Sir, obviously Jadzia has to leave... if something happened to her, it wouldn't take a doctor long to figure out she wasn't human. But you're still going to need help keeping the hostages alive, so if it's all the same to you... I'll stay.
All right... See if you can get her combadge back... (glances at wall monitor) I'll keep trying to log onto the Net.
The police cut off our access.
That's one problem I might be able to help you with.
Do you really think you can convince your friend to put us on the Net?
It'll take some persuading... but I think he'll do what's right...
This is it. The men who took my combadge brought me here before they took me to the Processing Center.
Hello?
There's nobody here.
We just want to talk.
Woosh! I'm invisible.
If you say so.
You can see me?
Just barely.
That's okay. As long as they can't see me.
Who?
The aliens. They'll suck your brains out... right through your ears.
I know... you see, I'm an alien, too...
I thought so... but you're a good alien.
I'm here to protect Earth from its enemies. But I need that piece of jewelry you're holding to do it.
I understand... here, take it. Good luck.
Thank you. And remember, don't tell anyone about this.
I won't... don't worry.
This is where I came in...
Julian... take care of yourself.
We'll see you at the beam-in site.
Let me see if I understand what you're asking me to do. You want me to override a government block, violate my Interface operating license, and turn my channels over to a bunch of criminals.
They're not criminals.
I know that, Jadzia, but they're acting like criminals. They've got guns, they've taken hostages...
So why do you think they're doing it? Don't you want to know? Don't you think the public deserves to know?
You're asking me to break the law.
I'm asking you to give those people a voice.

Chris, sooner or later, the government is going to retake the Sanctuary District. When that happens, a lot of people are going to die. And unless the public learns why the Sanctuary residents did what they did, all those deaths will be for nothing.
You know, I'll probably lose my license for this... But at least I'll get good ratings.

... my name is Henry Garcia... and I've been living here two years now... I came to San Francisco to work in a brewery... but they laid a bunch of us off when they got some new equipment... and so I ended up here.
I've never been in trouble with the law or anything... I don't want to hurt anybody... I just want a chance to work and live like regular people...

Governor, I understand your concern... but I think the use of force would be premature at this time. I am aware that there have been disturbances in other Sanctuary Districts, but we have to think about the hostages. I know. I've heard the rumors, too. But that's all they are, rumors. If you just give me another chance to talk with Webb and Bell... Yes, sir. Of course. We'll do our best.
scene: 37   EXT. OUTSIDE THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: The Governor's made up his mind. We move in at oh five hundred.
scene: 37   EXT. OUTSIDE THE SANCTUARY DISTRICT GATE - DAY #4

quote: No luck?
Afraid not.
Well, we know one thing. They arrived before the year twenty-forty-eight.
How can you be sure?
Because we were just there. And that wasn't the mid-twenty-first century that I read about in school. It's been changed. Earth history had its rough patches, but never that rough.
If we limit our search to dates before twenty-forty-eight, how many possibilities does that leave us.
According to my calculations, three. But we've only got enough chroniton particles for one more try.
Pick one, Chief. And let's hope you get lucky.
That's my best guess.
That's good enough for me.
Energize.
Kira to Sisko.
I'm picking up a combadge distress signal. It's Dax.
Kira to Dax.
Kira...
Dax, am I glad to hear your voice.
Where are you?
We should be in the exact location where you beamed in.
I'll meet you there.
Are Sisko and Bashir with you?
No... I'll explain everything when I see you.
The transporter is set to automatically retrieve us in about a minute. You'd better deactivate your combadge.
Acknowledged.
We'll reactivate them tomorrow in time for the next beam out.
Should be an interesting day...
-- best ball club I ever saw?
The ninety-nine Yankees, no doubt about it.
Get out of here. The fifteen Kings could've taken them any day. Am I right?
I wouldn't know. I prefer tennis, actually.
Soccer...
It's up to you, Bell.
I don't think there's any question. The Kings. Fifteen was Buck Bokai's rookie year.
And that's all they had going for them.
I've been up on the roof... looks like another National Guard unit just arrived. Something's going on out there.
All right, everyone on your feet.
What are you doing?
(indicating Lee's cubicle) They'll be safer in there. Let's go.
I want you in there with them. Make sure they keep their heads down.
I'll see if I can find something to block the doorway.
Danny, wake up...
Time for you to go.
But I want to stay here with you.
I'll meet up with you later.
Tell your mom that I love her... and give your sister a kiss for me. Go on, now...
Hey, kid.
Yeah, I thought so. It looks good on you... now get lost.
What the hell. It's probably raining in Tasmania, anyway.
I'm going to talk to Preston, find out what's going on.
My god...
Stop shooting, dammit! We're okay!
I'm a hostage, you idiot!
Blue leader, this is team one... the Processing Center is secure...
What's wrong with you people; you could've gotten us all killed.
There were rumors you were dead.
Do I look dead to you?
Our orders were to pacify the building...
(looking around at the bodies; sarcastic) Well you certainly did a good job.
Leave him alone.
I copy... There's trouble on second street...
Go pacify second street. Officer Calvera and I can handle things in here.
All right. Let's move.
How is he?
Lucky... he'll live...
Next time I tell you to stay down...
Gotcha...
What about Webb?
How could we have let this happen...
The question is... how do we stop it from happening again...
(to Vin, re: Sisko and Bashir) So what do we do with them?
I don't know...
You could let us go.
All right.
Vin...
They saved our lives back there.
How will we explain what happened to them?
Give me your I.D. cards.
We'll switch these with two of the casualties. As far as anyone will know, you both died here. That okay with you, Bell?
Thanks...
My pleasure.
Come on, let's get you out of here.
Anything else we can do for you?
There is one thing.
Name it.
Tell people the truth about what happened in here.
I would've done that anyway...
First Officer's Log, Supplemental. Upon returning to the present with our missing crewmembers, we were relieved to discover that the timeline had been restored.
Come in.
How do you feel?
Better.
I thought you'd want to see this... I found it in the historical database.
I'm not looking forward to explaining this to Starfleet Command.
Well... at least it's a good picture.
Commander... after seeing a little bit of the twenty-first century... there's one thing I still don't understand... how could they have let things get so bad... ?
That's a good question... I wish I had an answer...
Jake!
Leanne. I thought you were on Bajor.
I came back early. You know, I was just thinking about you.
Really?
Yeah... I passed by the Klingon restaurant and I was thinking about the time you and I and Orak were having dinner...
And you ordered the gagh...
How is Orak? I haven't talked to him in awhile.
We stopped seeing each other a few weeks ago.
Oh.
So... are you doing anything tomorrow night?
I'm supposed to be playing dom-jot with Nog.
But they're not really firm plans. In fact, I was thinking of canceling them.
Really? Well... if you do cancel... would you be interested in... dinner?
Sure.
Great. How 'bout eighteen hundred at the Klingon restaurant?
I'll be there. But this time we'll skip the gagh.
Definitely. See you then.
Look out!
Move aside!
What do we have?
Bajoran transport coming in. They said there was some kind of accident on board and they've got casualties.
They're docking...
We should've beamed the wounded directly to the Infirmary.
They have a loose plasma coil. We couldn't beam through the radiation.
Docking clamps secure. I'm opening the airlock. Stand back.
Come on.
It's going to be all right...
I've got you.
This way, Eminence.
Kai Winn... ?
The Vedek... take care of the Vedek...
Odo to Kira.
Kira here. INTERCUT:
I think you should meet us in the Infirmary, Major. Vedek Bareil was on the transport... and he's been injured.
Station Log: Stardate 48498.4 A Bajoran transport carrying both Kai Winn and Vedek Bareil has docked at the station following an accident which nearly destroyed the vessel.
Chief O'Brien tells me that your ship suffered some kind of failure in the plasma relay. You're lucky to be alive.
The Prophets must have decided that my work here is not yet complete. How is Bareil?
Still in surgery.
His heart rate is falling. Fifty units inoprovaline.
Severe cerebral edema... with damage to the cerebral artery... and the neuroglial network.
His vital signs are deteriorating too quickly, we can't wait any longer. Prep him for surgery.
The report on the transport, sir.
Give me the short version.
There was a molecular fracture in one of the warp plasma conduits. It was only a matter of time until it gave way... once it collapsed the entire relay system exploded.
Was it sabotage?
I don't think so.
Why would you suspect sabotage?
I'd prefer to discuss that with the Emissary in private.
Put a pressor field on that artery.
The arterial disruption is too severe... the pressor can't stop the hemorrhaging.
All right... clamp off the artery for now and increase the plasma level to maximum.
Cardiac arrest.
He can't take much more of that...
His arterial pressure is falling...
I see it.
Neurotransmitter levels are falling too...
Two cc's cordrazine.
Do it.
Synaptic failure!

Vedek Bareil and I were on our way to a secret meeting with a member of the Cardassian Central Command. It was my intention to open talks between Bajor and Cardassia which would lead to a treaty... and to a final peace settlement.
You have been negotiating peace... with Cardassia...
The Prophets teach us that while violence may keep an enemy at bay... only peace can make him a friend.
How long has this been going on?
Bareil has been working to set up this meeting with Legate Turrel for the past five months. They've discussed issues ranging from war reparations to an exchange of ambassadors.
They've even discussed the possibility
Please don't take this the wrong way... but I never would've guessed that you would be the one to bring such a... bold vision of peace to Bajor.
A large share of the credit goes to Vedek Bareil. Without him, the talks would've never come this far.
It sounds like you've developed a deeper appreciation for Vedek Bareil.

I have to admit... he's been a very... loyal and trustworthy aide since the election. I'm not sure I could've been as... forgiving if I'd been in his place. These talks were his idea... he's guided me through them... and without him in the future... the talks may never resume.
I'm sorry. The radiation severely damaged his neural pathways. I did everything I could.
I know you did. Did he ever regain consciousness?
No. I don't think he suffered.
Thank you, Doctor. I'm on duty in Ops. Excuse me.
Kira.
I think they can get along without you in Ops today.
Maybe so. But I need to be there. I appreciate your concern... but I'll grieve in my own way... in my own time.
We're ready to begin the autopsy, Doctor.
Release the stasis field.
Let's begin with a neural scan. I want to map his central axonal pathways and find out exactly where the breakdown began.
Should I begin taking neural tissue samples?
Looks like the damage began in the parietal lobe... and spread through the rest of his brain in a retrograde manner.
Wait a minute... A neuron just fired in his cerebral cortex.
There it is again.
His nerves... his nerves are still transmitting electrical impulses to his brain...
How can that be? His brain activity level is zero. His nervous system should be completely inactive.
I don't know... but it means that his body is still capable of sending messages to the brain... except the brain can't process those messages.
The radiation he was exposed to might have fortified his peripheral cell membranes...
The radiation has also left a residual imprint of the original axonal pathways in his brain.
If we could regenerate his pathways using his own neuron cells... it might be possible to revive him...
What about brain damage? There's
He was in stasis most of that time... that, combined with the strengthening of his cell membranes from the radiation might buy us the time we need...
We need to repolarize his nerve cells with electrical impulses. The spino- thalamic tract will transmit that directly to the cerebral cortex.
If the burst is the proper intensity, it might create a cascade effect within his brain. The neurons might resume their normal firing patterns...
Let's close up the cranial cavity.
Neurogenic stimulators are in place... let's try a fifty millivolt burst.
Increase to sixty.
Seventy.
That's five millivolts above what normal tissue can withstand. It'll burn out his cerebral cortex.
If I'm right... the inoprovaline drug I gave him should provide additional resistance against the excess electro-stimulation.
Seventy.
Doctor...
... it's too early to tell for certain, but I'm hoping he'll make a full recovery. He may even be back on his feet again in a few weeks.
You say that so calmly. But it's not every doctor that loses a patient and then has him back on his feet in a few weeks.
Indeed, you're far too modest. You've performed nothing less than a miracle here... the Prophets must walk with you, Doctor.
Well, I -- and the Prophets, were lucky that the ionizing radiation left a residual signature on Bareil's axonal pathways. That's what really made this possible.
Whoever deserves... the credit... I am... grateful, Doctor.
And I am grateful that you were not taken from us, Vedek Bareil.
My work here... is not... yet finished.

No... it is not. We must resume the negotiations immediately. We can't risk losing the momentum we've established. I would like to send a coded message to Legate Turrel... and invite him to come to DS Nine to continue the talks.
Wait a minute. Bareil's in no condition to conduct negotiations.
Bareil will simply be advising me, Doctor. I will conduct the actual talks.
I'll allow it as long as your visits don't tire him.
Agreed. We will speak again soon.
Eminence...
So... are we still playing springball next month?
You bet... but I think I'll have an unfair advantage.
You mean playing against a dead man?
No... I mean I've been practicing.
My Dad said you were looking for me.
Yeah. Uh... it's about tomorrow night...

Don't worry, I've already taken care of it. I met these three Terrellians who were bragging about how great they are at dom-jot. So I arranged a game... us against them -- a strip of latinum a game, double-back rules.
Look, Nog... we have a little problem...
No we don't. I guarantee that we can beat them.
It's not that. I just can't do it tomorrow night.
But it has to be tomorrow night. They're leaving the next day.
I... I made other plans.
What could be more important than dom-jot?
I have a date.
Oh. Well, that's different.
It is?
Yeah. Money is money, but women are better.
Is that a Rule of Acquisition?
It's a personal rule. So, who is she?
Leanne.
Leanne! Way to go, Jake.
So, what's the name of my date? I hope she's as cute as Leanne.
Your date?
She is humanoid isn't she?
Nog... Leanne invited me out. You... never came up in the conversation.
A pretty girl asks you out on a date and you get confused. I understand.
Good.
So... she has a friend, right?
Well, I'm sure she does...
Then tell her to bring her along.
Nog, that's not what I had in mind.
That's because you were confused. Would you rather the three of us go out?
Well, when you put it that way...
Exactly. One thing, Jake... you're still pretty new at this dating business... just promise me you won't do anything to embarrass me.
I'll do my best.
(smiling in anticipation) This is going to be great. I may even wash my lobes.
You know Julian, I've been thinking. Once you publish your work on this case, they'll probably name a building after you at Starfleet Medical.
I doubt that.
Maybe a statue... you and your trusty tricorder, pushing the bounds of medical knowledge.
Jadzia, you're such a romantic.
What about a plaque? A nice big plaque.
Julian, I'm just kidding.
It's not that. Bareil's circulatory system is starting to fail.
I suggest that we put off any discussion of the Cardassians returning the Orbs until after diplomatic relations have been established.
That will only delay an inevitable argument.
But it will give the peace process a chance to grow. Once the Cardassians are invested in the process, it may be easier to discuss matters like this.
Very well.
A wise decision, Eminence.
I hope so, Vedek Bareil. The first meeting with Turrel is scheduled for tomorrow afternoon. I will see you again before then.
You're not here to deliver good news, I take it?

To revive you, I had to flood your nervous system with neurogenic radiation. Unfortunately, it looks as though that caused some kind of selective vaso-constriction in your arteries. The result is an inadequate blood flow to your internal organs.
So what do we do?
We need to place you back in stasis and do more research on your condition.
For how long?
I can't say right now. It could be days, weeks... even months.
Maybe even years... ?
Maybe.

I'm sorry, Doctor, but that's not acceptable. I can't allow myself to be put "in storage" when my people need me. I don't want to wake up to find a Bajor still haunted by the memory of the occupation.
I realize how important these talks are to Bajor... but as your physician my duty is to you first.
And my duty is to Bajor. Help me heal my people. That's all that matters to me, Doctor.

You could say I'm making up for past mistakes. Winn would never have been selected Kai if I hadn't dropped out of the election. A lot of people were counting on me to lead Bajor. They were... shocked when I backed out.
But you can't risk your life just to look better in their eyes.
I want to look better in my own eyes. This is important to me. I want to bring a lasting peace to Bajor and Cardassia. It's why the Prophets spared my life when the plasma relay exploded...
and it's why they let you bring me back to life.

There is an experimental drug -- called Vasokin -- that would increase the blood flow to your organs and might allow you to function normally for a while. But there's a great deal of risk associated with it.
What sort of risk?
In twenty-two percent of the cases on record, Vasokin has severely damaged the patient's heart, lungs, and kidneys... sometimes the brain. In your condition, it could even be fatal.
But it would allow me to function normally for the next few days?
Yes. But are those few days worth risking your life?

I have no great desire to die, Doctor. But I am determined to carry out the will of the Prophets as long as I'm able... and I can't carry out their will if I'm lying unconscious in a stasis tube. Please Doctor... begin the Vasokin treatments.
All right. We'll begin this afternoon. I just hope we don't come to regret this.
So do I..

Station Log: Supplemental. Legate Turrel has arrived aboard the station to resume the negotiations. Vedek Bareil suggested that I sit in on the talks as an impartial observer, and Kai Winn has agreed.
Perhaps you didn't hear me. There are no Bajoran prisoners left in Cardassian hands.
Maybe we should redefine our terms. Perhaps there are no official prisoners... but could there be a number of, shall we say... detainees?
There are, of course, people being detained in the Justice Ministry for crimes against the state.

But that's a discussion for another time. Let's move on. I'd like to discuss what you've called "war reparations." We would be willing to pay for the destruction of all Bajoran property incurred during the occupation... as long as you are willing to return to us all Cardassian equipment and property left behind on Bajor.
What sort of... property?
Anything that is clearly of Cardassian origin and that was inadvertently left on Bajor when our forces pulled out.
Could you be more specific?
Of course. I can provide lists of material... equipment... as long as we have an agreement in principle that anything of Cardassian origin does still belong to the Cardassian people.
I... will consider your offer.
Good. Just remember that my offer to pay war reparations is linked to your acceptance of this principle. After all, it is our property we're asking to return. Shall we take a recess?
He's up to something.
That much seems clear.
But what? Why is he insisting on this... principle of his? And what about that demand for mining rights he made earlier? What was that all about?
I wish I could be of more help... but without knowing the entire negotiating record of the talks, it's hard to see the larger strategy at work.
I need Bareil. He's the only one who knows the entire negotiating record. Bareil's been talking with Turrel for months... he understands him... respects him... I think he even likes him.
I'm afraid you may have to face the possibility that Bareil may not be able to help you much longer.
I was chosen by the Prophets to lead our people into a new era... I know that. But I was never meant to sit in a room with a Cardassian and debate legalisms and "diplomatic nuances."
I can't do this without Bareil. If he dies... then peace with Cardassia dies with him.

My father used to take me to the wilderness preserves on Vulcan. So for years I thought their whole planet was like that -- animals and plants everywhere. I didn't know there were any people on Vulcan.
Boy, does she talk a lot for a female.
Excuse me?
Riska... weren't you telling me your uncle runs a bar on Osinar Six? You know, Nog's uncle runs this bar.
Is that right?
Let's not make foolish conversation. Just sit there and look beautiful.
Nog, what do you think you're doing?

Jake... I think I know how to handle females. Jake, you know I was thinking... after we're done eating, we could take these females into the holosuites. I borrowed one of my uncle's private programs: "The Massacre of Ferris Nine." I thought we'd spend an hour pillaging and looting the frightened townspeople.
I don't think so.
No one's asking you to think, my dear. (gives her his plate of food) Here, make yourself useful. Cut up my food for me.
You're joking, right?
She's so dumb. She's perfect.
That's it.
Wait, you're not going?
I suppose you want me to sit here and cut up your food, too?
I never said anything about cutting --
I hope you and your friend have fun in the holosuites.
Nog...
Don't say another word, Jake. I think you've done enough damage for one night.
Me?
Yeah, you. You were treating my female as if she was an equal.
And you were behaving like an idiot. This is the last time I do you a favor, Nog. From now on, you get your own dates.
And you can find someone else to play dom-jot with.
Fine!
Good!

Turrel is trying... to get a concession from you that I already... rejected. Tell him the question of... Cardassian property on Bajor was dealt with in the armistice talks four years ago. Don't worry... he'll still pay the reparations.
What about this question of mining rights?
His attention has been wandering and he's in pain. Give him more of the drug.
He's had enough.
Then you need to give him something else. The negotiations resume in less than six hours and we have over forty pages of --

Listen to me. I don't care about your negotiations, and I don't care about your treaty. All I care about is my patient and at the moment, he needs more medical care and less politics. Now, you can leave here willingly or I'll call security and have you removed.
You won't have to call them. I'll do it myself.
Put yourself in the hands of the Prophets, Bareil. They will not forsake you.
Yes... Eminence.
Anything I can do... ?
Just... be here.
I'm getting to... dislike seeing that look... on your face, Doctor.
As I feared, the Vasokin has begun to damage your internal organs. The damage is irreversible.
What happens now?

I can replace the damaged organs with artificial implants. But as long as you're taking the drug, I can't guarantee that the damage won't spread. I think you should reconsider letting me put you in stasis.
I'm afraid my mind's made up, Doctor. Just get me through these negotiations... I must carry out the will of the Prophets. Please. Whatever it takes... just do it.
Are you going to call security and have me removed from this room now, Doctor?
It hadn't occurred to me... yet.
How is Bareil?
The organ replacement surgery went well. He's still unconscious, but he should be awake within the hour.
Good. There are several points I still have to discuss with him before the next negotiating session.
That's why I'm here. When you see Bareil... I want you to tell him that you don't need him... that you can complete these negotiations without him.
But I do need him, Doctor.
I realize that. But I want you to tell him that you don't.
You seem to be asking me to lie.
I'm asking you to free Bareil from his obligations to you. And the only way he'll accept that is if you say he's no longer needed... that you can do this alone. Now, if that's a lie... then so be it.
That doesn't sound like a... Starfleet officer.

I'm a doctor first. And right now, I'm trying to give my patient his best chance to live. The way to do that is to put him in stasis. Bareil knows that... but his desire to complete these negotiations is so strong that he's forcing me to keep him conscious and mentally alert, even though it may kill him.
None of us wants that to happen, Doctor. But unless I'm mistaken... the decision regarding Bareil's treatment is up to him.
Yes... as the patient, it's his right to make that choice. But I'm asking you to help me change his mind.
Eminence... you're the Kai... these are your negotiations... let this be your moment in history. Finish the talks on your own and you won't have to share the credit with anyone.
You say that as though success is guaranteed, Doctor...
Of course. If the talks fail, you need someone to accept the blame, a scapegoat... you're a coward... you're afraid to stand alone!
Bareil's already made his decision, Doctor... I won't interfere.
And Doctor... I will not forget what you've said here.
Neither will I.
So... you never told me about your double-date...
Not much to tell...
That's not what I hear. Quark tells me that you and Nog aren't speaking to one another.
You should've seen the way he acted, Dad. He was acting like a spoiled brat. I've never been so embarrassed. I don't think Leanne will ever speak to me again.
So what did he do?

All kinds of stupid things. Riska couldn't say two words without him telling her to be quiet... he insisted that she cut up his food before he'd eat it... he treated her like she was some kind of slave.
And you're surprised?
Yeah. Aren't you?
It sounds like he's acting like a Ferengi to me. You can't really blame him for that.
Well, in that case, maybe you were right all along.
About what?
You once said that Humans and Ferengis are too different to ever really be friends.
I remember saying that... and you know what? I was wrong. You and Nog proved that. Sure, you have your cultural differences, but there's a real bond between you.
Well, I know one thing... I'm never going to set him up on a date again.
That's probably not a bad idea. I think you two should talk this over before it gets to be too big a problem.
I'm not sure Nog's going to be willing to talk to me so soon.
Well... I guess you'll just have to do something to get his attention.
Physician, heal thyself...
Doctor Bashir to the Infirmary. Medical Emergency.
On my way.
What happened?
I don't know.
Two cc's morphenolog. It's going to be all right. I'm going to help you.
I left instructions that he wasn't to have visitors for another three hours.
It's not her fault. Bareil called me himself... said he had some ideas on the treaty.
And you just couldn't wait to hear them.

The left temporal lobe is showing signs of massive synaptic failure. I hope you got all the advice you needed, Eminence... the Vasokin has damaged his brain. And I'm afraid the damage... is irreversible.
Will he regain consciousness?
Not in his present condition.
You were able to replace some of his internal organs with artificial implants... could you do something similar with the damaged areas of his brain?
I'm not sure we should pursue that option.
But it is an option.

There have been cases where small portions of the brain have been replaced with implants. But in this instance I'd have to replace his entire left hemisphere. There's a good chance he might lose something in the process.
What do you mean exactly? His memory? His personality?

It's hard to say with any certainty. There's still a great deal about the way the brain operates that we don't understand. One of my professors in medical school used to say that the brain had a "spark of life" that can't be replicated. If we begin replacing parts of Bareil's brain with artificial implants, that spark may be lost.
But you're saying if we don't do it, Bareil will never regain consciousness, and he'll die.
I think we need to consider what Bareil would want us to do.
Vedek Bareil wanted to continue with the negotiations, no matter what the cost.
With all due respect, your Eminence, you're hardly an impartial observer here. You have a personal interest in these talks.
There's more at stake than just one man's life.
One man's life is all I'm concerned about at the moment.
I think she's right, Julian. I think Bareil would want the positronic implant.
Kira... if I go through with this, the man who wakes up may not be the man you used to know.

I realize that... but I know how important this was to him... and I know he wouldn't just want to be put into stasis indefinitely, waiting for a medical solution that may never come. Do the operation, Julian. Let him finish what he started.
I'd like to talk to the doctor alone for a moment.

I just want you to know that as far as I'm concerned, your word is final in this situation. If you feel it's wrong to proceed with the operation, then that's the way it'll be. Kai Winn can protest all she wants... but I'll support you.
Thank you.
Mister Sisko.
Odo, I'd like you to do me a favor.
This is outrageous! I didn't steal anything from the Tholian Ambassador!
Just another innocent man arrested for a crime he didn't commit.
What's he doing here?
As if you didn't know. Your accomplice here denied involvement as well... but I have an eyewitness who saw both of you breaking into the Tholian Ambassador's quarters last night.
I don't even know what a Tholian looks like!
Tell it to the Magistrate.
At least put me in my own cell.
I'm sorry the accommodations aren't to your liking. Please feel free to submit a complaint to the management.
The positronic implant is functioning normally... the mid-brain interface is on-line... and he's awake.
Bareil?
Yes, Major.
How do you feel?
I'm... awake. Everything is... different.
Different in what way?
It's hard to explain... but when you touch me... it doesn't seem real... it's more like... a distant memory of a touch...
Vedek... do you remember the negotiations? I have some questions for you.
Of course, I do Eminence. The negotiations. A giant puzzle that needs to be solved.
It's a little more important than a puzzle.
If the Vedek chooses to look at the talks as a puzzle, then so be it. All that's important is that he helps me solve the puzzle.
I'll do all I can.
Something's wrong...
No kidding...

That's not what I mean. My father told me that if I got caught stealing again, he was going to send me back to live on the Ferengi homeworld with my grandmother. So where is he? Why isn't he here yelling and threatening me? And where's Uncle Quark? I'm late for work. And come to think of it, what are you doing here?
Ask Odo.

No, no, no. Throwing you in here wasn't Odo's idea. You don't just arrest the station commander's son without some really strong evidence. And I know there is no evidence because I know we didn't do anything. So why are we here, Jake?
All right... I put Odo up to it because I wanted to talk to you.
In here?
I didn't think you'd listen to me otherwise.
Well, this better be good.
I wanted to say... I'm sorry. I guess I just forgot you're a Ferengi.
You forgot? To most people, the lobes are a dead giveaway.
What I mean is... we spend so much time together... and we seem so much alike... I sometimes forget we're different.
I know we're different. Anyone who would talk to a female with such fawning respect is no Ferengi. It made me sick.
You want to talk about sick? Sick is making Riska cut up your food for you.
At least I didn't have her chew it for me.
Chew it?
That's right. In traditional Ferengi homes, the female softens the food with her teeth before serving it to the male.
That is disgusting.
I knew you'd react that way, which is why I didn't ask her to do it.
Well, do you have any other disgusting Ferengi customs I should know about?
Plenty. And you have plenty of human customs that disgust me.
Great. So we both disgust each other. You know, as we get older, this is just going to get worse. But I know one thing... I don't want to lose you as a friend.
Well, in that case double-dating is definitely out.
Agreed. And I guess we'll have to deal with the rest of our disgusting habits as they come up.
I guess so. You feel better?
Yeah.
Good. Now can we get out of here?
Sure. Odo? Odo? He's just playing around. Odo!
Station Log, Supplemental. Kai Winn has announced that Legate Turrel has signed the peace treaty. The news has sent a shockwave throughout the quadrant...
And although there is still some opposition from hard-line elements on both Bajor and Cardassia... it looks as though they're finally willing to put their long conflict behind them.
Remind me not to invite you to my next party.
Sorry. I guess I am sort of casting a pall over this gathering.
No one expects you to provide the entertainment, Julian. But you should try to enjoy yourself. After all, this celebration is for you, too.
Frankly, I'm not sure what I've done deserves a celebration.
Julian... you saved his life. You kept him alive against incredible odds. No matter what happens, you should always be proud of that.
Excuse me, your Eminence.
Yes?
Kai Winn, allow me to introduce... "Kai Winn."
I don't understand.
In honor of this occasion, I've named my latest creation after you. It's a chocolate souffle with Haligian tongue sauce.
I'm honored.
And you're also very popular. Believe me, I can't keep up with the orders so far.
Doctor Bashir to the Infirmary. Medical emergency.
Excuse me.
It's the other half of his brain, isn't it?
But you can still help him can't you? You can replace the other half of his brain with a positronic matrix.
I'm sorry, Nerys. But, this is where it ends.
What do you mean?
I won't remove the last shred of whatever humanity Bareil has left.
But it can be done.
Perhaps, my child, it's time to listen to Doctor Bashir.
Sure, now that you've got your peace treaty and you're assured of a place in history, you don't need Bareil anymore.
Believe me child, I share your pain. But I think the Prophets are calling to Bareil. I will see to it that Bajor never forgets him. (beat, then a good- bye) Doctor.
Julian... you can't stop now. You've got to keep going.

Nerys, if I remove the rest of his brain... put a machine in its place... he may look like Bareil... and he may even talk like Bareil... but it won't be Bareil. The "spark of life" will be gone. He'll be dead. And I'll be the one who killed him.
But if we do nothing... he'll die.
Yes, he will. But he'll die as a man... not a machine. Please... don't make me fight you on this. Just... let him go.
How long?
It will be about three hours until all brain activity ceases.
I'd like to stay here until then.
Of course.

Well... you got your treaty after all. I just wish there'd been more time for us. There's so much I never got to say to you. But this is all the time we have left, isn't it? So I guess I better say it now.

I'll never forget the first time I saw you... that day you came to the station. There was a serenity about you... like you had all the answers... It really got on my nerves for a while. But as I got to know you... I realized that you were just as confused as the rest of us... you just accepted your confusion better than anyone I'd ever met. And that's when I knew I loved you...
-- Doctor, I just don't see the value in this man's work.
Garak, Shakespeare is one of the giants of human literature.
I knew Brutus was going to kill Caesar in the first act, but Caesar doesn't figure it out until the knife is in his back...
That's why it's a tragedy. Caesar couldn't conceive that his best friend would plot his murder.

Tragedy is not the word I would use, farce would be more appropriate. Supposedly, this man is the leader of an entire empire, a brilliant military tactician, yet he can't see what's going on under his very nose --
Are you in a hurry, Doctor?
I have to get back to the Infirmary. There's a lot of work to do this afternoon.
You're lucky. I have more time on my hands than I know what to do with.
You could finish those pants I dropped off last week.
Tomorrow.
You're going to give yourself indigestion.
And I'll have you to thank for it. If you hadn't been late, I'd be able to enjoy my lunch.
This isn't the first time I've seen you rush through a meal. You never take the time to savor your food. It seems to be a human characteristic.
Look over there... that Talarian isn't even half finished with his meal, but his human companion's plate is empty.
Maybe he and I should get together for dessert and leave you and the Talarian to wile away the afternoon.

It's a very interesting sociological trait, don't you think? For generations now, humankind has had more than enough food... yet you all eat as if you were afraid someone was going to come along and take your plate away.
Garak, why don't you eat for a while and let me talk?
Fear of starvation amid plenty... it points to some dark secret hidden in the human soul... a gnawing hunger. Someone should do a study.
Why don't you do it? You're the one with all the free time on your hands.
If you want to have dessert, go ahead. I won't be offended.
I have to go. I'm sorry to leave while you're still eating.
No, no... I'm done, as well.
But you're only half finished.
If you really must know, I've been nibbling on Delavian chocolates all morning.
How did you get your hands on Delavian chocolates?
I promised my... supplier that I wouldn't tell. But since I deprived you of dessert, I'd be happy to bring some by the Infirmary later this afternoon.
Thanks, I'd like that.
Until then, Doctor...
Julian...
Major...
About those atmospheric specifications you requested for the Yalosian Ambassador...
Sixty percent nitrogen, ten percent benzene, and the rest hydrogen fluoride, as I recall...
We ran a test in one of the guest quarters... the mixture was so corrosive it started to dissolve the carpet.
Don't look at me, it's what they breathe...
Then I guess we'll just have to pull the carpet out...
Just be sure you don't replace it with anything red or orange...
Why not?
They can't see that part of the color spectrum.
Is there anything else I should know about Yalosians...
As a matter of fact...
Bashir to Infirmary... Medical emergency on the Promenade...
Garak's shop...
Are you all right... ?
As well as could be expected...
But I'm afraid your pants won't be ready tomorrow, after all...
Report.
The explosion was caused by a rupture in the power conduit behind this wall.
What caused the rupture?
Probably an overload in the ODN juncture.
I take it you don't agree.
Let's just say I find it odd that a conduit running behind Garak's shop would "happen" to overload.
So you think someone ruptured it deliberately.
I wouldn't be surprised. It stands to reason that a man with Garak's past would have enemies.
Commander... I'm detecting traces of nitrilin.
Nitrilin is extremely unstable.
And very rare. It couldn't have come from the power conduit.
It could be the residue from a micro- explosive device planted on the conduit and rigged to cause a rupture...
Making it look like the explosion was an accident.
Exactly.
Sisko to Ops.
